poss. stack corruption issues

===========================================
native builtin raising an exception mid-call corrupts the stack:
===========================================

Repro (run inside a function, not top-level):

import os;

func readAll(path) {
    var fp = os.open(path, "r");
    var lines = [];
    try {
        while (true) {
            lines.append(os.readln(fp));
        }
    } except EOFError as e {
        os.close(fp);
    }
    print type(lines);   // prints "builtin", not "list" -- lines got clobbered
    return lines;
}

Root cause: ReadlnBuiltIn (src/builtin/os_functions.go, EOF case) calls
vm.RaiseExceptionByName(...) directly from inside the native Go function,
instead of going through vm.RunTimeError()+ErrorMsg like every other builtin
error. RaiseExceptionByName -> raiseException immediately rewinds
vm.stackTop to the try handler's saved StackTop and redirects frame.Ip to the
handler -- but the call site that invoked the native function (callValue's
builtin branch, vm.go ~1803, and invokeFromBuiltin, vm.go ~1929) has no idea
this happened and unconditionally does its own post-call bookkeeping
afterward anyway (vm.stackTop -= argCount+1; vm.stack[vm.stackTop] = res;
vm.stackTop++). That double-adjustment writes the native function's return
value into whatever local now occupies the slot the exception handler
rewound to -- in the repro above, the `lines` local declared right before
the try.

Only affects exceptions raised via RaiseExceptionByName called *directly*
from inside a native Go function body (bypassing ErrorMsg). The normal
`raise` statement (OP_RAISE) and vm.RunTimeError()-reported errors are fine,
because those go through the dispatch loop's `End:` label, which calls
refreshFrame() at the right point and never races with a native call's own
bookkeeping.

Likely fix: add a VM flag set by raiseException right before it returns true
(handler found), checked by callValue/invokeFromBuiltin immediately after
calling the native function -- if set, skip the stack bookkeeping entirely
(the handler path already left stack/frame correct) instead of redoing it.

Probably also corrupts the same way at top-level (not just inside a
function) since the arithmetic bug isn't frame-relative -- just less
noticeable there because the clobbered slot usually isn't a live named local.
Worth double-checking whether this is the same root cause as the vaguer
"poss. stack corruption issues" note below.

Workaround used for json.load(): added os.read_all(path) (native, reads the
whole file in Go and reports errors via vm.RunTimeError like every other os
builtin) instead of a readln-loop + except EOFError inside a function, so
json.load never hits this path.

